          <p class="fp-intro">
            Cookies get all the press. Fingerprinting is why the press coverage barely matters.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="fp-analogy">
          <div class="fp-analogy-card">
            <div class="fp-analogy-icon">✍️</div>
            <h3>The handwriting analogy</h3>
            <p>Imagine a letter with no signature and no return address. You still might recognize the handwriting — the way someone forms their letters, their spacing, their pressure on the pen. Handwriting is unique without being labeled.</p>
            <p>Your browser has handwriting. Every website you visit receives a detailed technical profile of your browser and device: the exact browser version, your operating system, your screen resolution, your installed fonts, your timezone, your graphics card capabilities, your language settings, the plugins you've installed, and dozens of other attributes. Individually, most are common. Combined, the profile is statistically unique to you — across sessions, across websites, and across IP addresses.</p>
            <p>No cookie needed. No login required. No consent banner changes anything.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fp-how-grid">
          <div class="fp-how-card">
            <div class="fp-how-icon">🧩</div>
            <h4>How they collect it</h4>
            <p>JavaScript running on any webpage can query your browser for hundreds of attributes. Canvas fingerprinting renders invisible graphics and reads how your specific hardware renders them — the output varies subtly between GPU models, driver versions, and operating systems. Audio fingerprinting does the same with sound processing. These run silently, in milliseconds, every time you load a page.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="fp-how-card">
            <div class="fp-how-icon">📌</div>
            <h4>Why it's more durable than cookies</h4>
            <p>Cookies can be deleted, blocked, or rejected. Fingerprints are derived from your hardware and software — things you can't easily change. Clearing your cookies doesn't change your screen resolution or your GPU. A fingerprint can persist across browser restarts, private browsing sessions, and even different browsers on the same machine. It survives the "reject all" button entirely.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="fp-how-card">
            <div class="fp-how-icon">📋</div>
            <h4>What the EU cookie law actually covers</h4>
            <p>The GDPR and ePrivacy Directive require consent for cookies and similar tracking technologies. Courts are still debating whether fingerprinting requires consent — and many operators have concluded the legal risk is lower than the business cost of not tracking. When you click "reject all" on a cookie banner, you've addressed one specific technology. The fingerprinting script loading alongside the cookie consent manager may have already run.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

